  	<h2 class="title">
    <a id="link-48393" title="The Story Of One Man’s Pregnancy" class="browser-link" target="_blank" data-category="life" href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2018/mar/22/story-one-mans-pregnancy-trans-jason-barker">The Story Of One Man’s Pregnancy</a>
      <a class="category within-meta life" href="/link-categories/life">Life</a>
	</h2>

  	<div class="metadata clearfix">
      <a href="/author/paula-cocozza">Paula Cocozza</a> | <a href="/source/guardian">Guardian</a> | 22nd March 2018
      
  	</div>

    <a href="https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2018/mar/22/story-one-mans-pregnancy-trans-jason-barker"><img class="picture show-for-medium" src="https://the-browser-assets.s3.amazonaws.com/uploads/2018/03/Screen-Shot-2018-03-22-at-12.13.25-100x100.png" alt="Screen shot 2018 03 22 at 12.13.25 100x100" /></a>
      
  	<p class="content clearfix">
  		Men are getting pregnant, and have been doing so for years. In Australia, 54 people who identified as men gave birth in 2014. In London, Jason Barker has a son aged eight. “In pregnancy, Barker mostly passed as ‘a fat bloke’. No one offered him a seat on the bus. No one batted an eyelid when, dressed in jeans and a cardie, he walked along the canal towpath to Nando’s two days before giving birth. He was both in plain sight and, owing to the relative rarity of pregnant men, hidden”
  		<span class="time-to-read">(2,450 words)</span>
  	</p>

